Per-coordinate Setup . Let \(n&gt;1\), \(\alpha[t], \mathbf{w}[t], \mathbf{g}[t], \Delta[t+1] \in \mathbb{R}^{n 	imes 1}\) . For each coordinate \(i\), . \[ oxed{ {\mathbf{w}[t+1, i]} = {\mathbf{w}[t,i]} + {\Delta[t+1,i]} }\] \[ oxed{ \step }\] Let \(0 &lt; \mu \le 1\) be a trust-region penalty constant that enforces the per-iteration subproblem . \[ oxed{ 	robjsca = \stepmom + \mu\,\stepcorrng }\] Since . \( rac{d^2	robjsca}{d{}\alpha[t,i]^2} = \dengmom\), . the subproblem defined by \(	robjsca\) is strongly convex in \(\alpha[t,i]\). Let the normalized gradient be \(
grad =  rac{\mathbf{g}[t,i]}{\dengmomsqrt}\), where \(
umngradcorr=1\). Minimizing \(	robjsca\) w.r.t \(\alpha[t,i]\) gives . $$  oxed{  egin{align}\label{lrmom} \alpha[t,i] = \mu\, rac{
umngradcorr}{\dengmomsqrt} = \mu\, rac{1}{\dengmomsqrt} \end{align} } $$ Realizing this learning rate involves estimating the gradient‚Äôs moment at each iteration. More generally, . \[ oxed{ 	robjsca = \stepmom + \mu\,\stepcorru }\] So, instead of \(\mathbf{u}[t,i] 	riangleq 
grad\) as above, let \(\mathbf{u}[t,i] 	riangleq \mathbf{w}[t,i]\) . Minimizing \(	robjsca\) w.r.t \(\alpha[t,i]\) gives . $$  egin{align} \label{lrparcor}  oxed{ \alpha[t,i] = \mu\, rac{
umwgcorr}{\dengmomsqrt} } \end{align} $$ Realizing this learning rate involves estimating the gradient‚Äôs moment, and the weight-gradient partial correlation at each iteration. It turns out that minimizing the mean squared parameter error \(\mathbb{E}[\mathbf{\varepsilon}^2[t+1]]\) yields this same iteration-dependent optimal learning rate with \(\mu=1\). The derived optimal learning rates for the two trust-region subproblems are of a general iteration-dependent learning-rate oracle, in the form . \[\alpha[t,i] = \mu\,\Phi[t,i], \quad \Phi[t,i] =  rac{\mathbf{a}[t,i]}{\mathbf{d}[t,i]}.\] In general, we can replace the trust-region constant \(\mu\) with an iterative form \(0 \le \mu[t] \le 1\), where \(\mu[t]=\mu\,\digamma[t]\), and \(0\le \digamma[t] \le 1\). \[ oxed{  egin{aligned} \mathbf{w}[t+1,i] = \mathbf{w}[t,i] -\alpha[t,i]\,\mathbf{g}[t,i] \end{aligned} }\] $$  egin{aligned} &amp;\mathbf{m}[t, i] = \dengmom\ &amp;\mathbf{d}[t, i] = {\mathbf{m}[t]}^{ rac{1}{2}}\ &amp;
grad = {\mathbf{g}[t,i]}/{\mathbf{d}[t, i]} \ &amp; oxed{ \mathbf{a}[t, i] = egin{cases} &amp; 1 \ &amp; 
umngradcorr \ &amp; 
umwgcorr \end{cases} }\ &amp;\mathbf{w}[t+1,i] = \mathbf{w}[t,i] - \mu[t]\, \mathbf{a}[t, i] \,
grad \end{aligned} $$ . Matrix Setup . Now, in this setup, let \(n, m&gt;1\) we assume \(\mathbf{w}[t], \mathbf{g}[t], \Delta[t+1] \in \mathbb{R}^{n 	imes m}\), while \(\alpha[t] \in \mathbb{R}^{n 	imes n}\) and symmetric. \[ oxed{ \matstep }\] \[ oxed{ 	robjmat = \gmatstepmom + \mu\,\gmatstepcorrng }\] Rewriting, . \[ oxed{ 	robjmat = \matstepmom + \mu\,\matstepcorrng }\] Since . \( rac{d^2\mkern1pt	robjmat}{d\mkern1pt\alpha[t]^2} = \matdengmom \ge 0\). Let the normalized gradient be \(
matgrad = {\matdengmomsqrt}{\mathbf{g}[t]}\), where \(\matngradcorr=\mathbf{I}_{n	imes n}\). Minimizing \(	robjmat\) w.r.t \(\alpha[t]\) gives . $$  oxed{ \alpha[t] = \mu\mkern1pt{\matngradcorr}\mkern1pt{\matdengmomsqrt} = \mu\,{\matdengmomsqrt} } $$ . Similarly, minimizing . \[ oxed{ 	robjmat = \matstepmom + \mu\,\matstepcorru }\] where, instead of \(\mathbf{u}[t] 	riangleq 
matgrad\) as above, we have \(\mathbf{u}[t] 	riangleq \mathbf{w}[t]\) . leads to . $$  oxed{ \alpha[t] = \mu\mkern1pt{\matwngradcorr}\mkern1pt{\matdengmomsqrt} } $$ . The derived optimal learning rate matrix for the two trust-region subproblems are of a general iteration-dependent learning-rate oracle, in the form . \[\alpha[t] = \mu\,\Phi[t], \quad \Phi[t] = {\mathbf{a}[t]}\mkern1mu{ ar{\mathbf{d}}[t]} \in \mathbb{R}^{n 	imes n}.\] . \[ oxed{  egin{aligned} \mathbf{w}[t+1] = \mathbf{w}[t] -\alpha[t]\,\mathbf{g}[t] \end{aligned} }\] $$  egin{aligned} &amp;\mathbf{m}[t] = \matdengmom\ &amp; ar{\mathbf{d}}[t] = \mathbf{m}[t]^{	ext{-} rac{1}{2}}\ &amp;
matgrad =  ar{\mathbf{d}}[t] \mathbf{g}[t,i]\ &amp; oxed{ \mathbf{a}[t] =  egin{cases} &amp; 1 \ &amp; \matngradcorr \ &amp; \matwngradcorr \end{cases} }\ &amp;\mathbf{w}[t+1] = \mathbf{w}[t] - \mu[t]\,\mathbf{a}[t]\,
matgrad \end{aligned} $$ . with Smoothed Gradients . Per-coordinate Setup . Replace the stochastic gradient with a smoothed version: . \[ oxed{ \stepv }\] where the smoothed gradient \(\mathbf{v}[t,i] =  of\{\mathbf{g}[t,i]\}\), and \( of\) is a first-order filter with the transfer function: . \[H(z) = \eta \,  rac{1 - \gamma z^{-1}}{1 -  eta z^{-1}}, \quad 0 \le  eta &lt; 1, \ \gamma &lt;  eta\] where \( eta\) and \(\gamma\) are the tunable pole and zero parameters of the first-order filter. The multiplier \(\eta\) is a function of \( eta\) and \(\gamma\) chosen to ensure the mean value of both \(\mathbf{v}[t,i]\) and \(\mathbf{g}[t,i]\) are the same, \(\expv = \expg.\) Also, by the mean‚Äësquared input‚Äìoutput relation of an LTI system (Papoulis, 1977), with impulse response \(h[k]\), . \[\dengmomv \propto \zeta_{ eta,\gamma}\, \dengmom .\] where \(\zeta_{ eta,\gamma}\) is a variance reduction constant, whose maximum equals the energy of the LTI‚Äôs impulse response: \(\zeta_{ eta,\gamma} \le \sum_{k=0}^{\infty} h[k]^2 = {\eta^2} rac{1+\gamma^2-2\gamma eta}{(1- eta^2)}\). Repeating the learning-rate derivation with \(\mathbf{v}[t,i]\), . \[ oxed{ 	robjsca = \stepmom + \mu\,\stepcorrngv }\] yields . \[\alpha[t,i] = \mu\, rac{1}{\sqrt{\dengmomv}} = \mu^{\prime}\, rac{1}{\sqrt{\dengmom}}.\] The varaince reduction factor is a scaling constant, it can be removed by absorbing it into the trust‚Äëregion constant, with the rescaled trust‚Äëregion constant: . \[\mu^{\prime} 	riangleq  rac{\mu}{\sqrt{\zeta}} \subset (0, 1).\] Therefore, the derived per‚Äëcoordinate learning rate retains the same functional form (after absorbing the variance‚Äëreduction factor into a \(\mu \subset (0, 1)\)): . $$  oxed{ \alpha[t,i] = \mu\, rac{1}{\sqrt{\dengmom}} } $$ . \[ oxed{  egin{aligned} \mathbf{w}[t+1,i] = \mathbf{w}[t,i] -\alpha[t,i]\,\mathbf{v}[t,i] \end{aligned} }\] $$  egin{aligned} &amp;\mathbf{v}[t,i] =  of\{\mathbf{g}[t,i]\}\ &amp;\mathbf{m}[t, i] = \dengmom\ &amp;\mathbf{d}[t, i] = {\mathbf{m}[t]}^{ rac{1}{2}}\ &amp;
grad = {\mathbf{g}[t,i]}/{\mathbf{d}[t, i]} \ &amp;
gradv = {\mathbf{v}[t,i]}/{\mathbf{d}[t, i]} \ &amp; oxed{ \mathbf{a}[t, i] = egin{cases} &amp; 1 \ &amp; 
umngradvcorr \ &amp; 
umwvcorr \end{cases} }\ &amp;\mathbf{w}[t+1,i] = \mathbf{w}[t,i] - \mu[t]\, \mathbf{a}[t, i] \,
gradv \end{aligned} $$ . Matrix Setup . Now, in this setup, . \[\mathbf{v}[t] =  of\{\mathbf{g}[t]\}\] Let \(n, m&gt;1\) we assume \(\mathbf{w}[t], \mathbf{g}[t], \mathbf{v}[t], \Delta[t+1] \in \mathbb{R}^{n 	imes m}\), while \(\alpha[t] \in \mathbb{R}^{n 	imes n}\) and symmetric. \[ oxed{ \matstepv }\] \[ oxed{ 	robjmat = \gmatstepmom + \mu[t]\,\gmatstepcorrngv }\] Since . \( rac{d^2\mkern1pt	robjmat}{d\mkern1pt\alpha[t]^2} = \matdengmomv \ge 0\). Let the normalized smooth gradient be \(
matgradv = {\matdenvmomsqrt}{\mathbf{v}[t]}\), where \(\matngradvcorr=\mathbf{I}_{n	imes n}\). Minimizing \(	robjmat\) w.r.t \(\alpha[t]\) gives . $$  oxed{ \alpha[t] = \mu\mkern1pt{\matngradvcorr}\mkern1pt{\matdenvmomsqrt} = \mu\,{\matdenvmomsqrt} } $$ Unlike the per‚Äëcoordinate case, which normalizes using a scalar variance, the matrix case normalization uses a full covariance matrix, which automatically removes all variance‚Äëscaling effects from smoothing. \[ oxed{  egin{aligned} \mathbf{w}[t+1] = \mathbf{w}[t] -\alpha[t]\,\mathbf{v}[t] \end{aligned} }\] $$  egin{aligned} &amp;\mathbf{v}[t] =  of\{\mathbf{g}[t]\}\ &amp;\mathbf{m}[t] = \matdengmomv\ &amp; ar{\mathbf{d}}[t] = \mathbf{m}[t]^{	ext{-} rac{1}{2}}\ &amp;
matgradv =  ar{\mathbf{d}}[t] \mathbf{v}[t,i]\ &amp; oxed{ \mathbf{a}[t] =  egin{cases} &amp; 1 \ &amp; \matngradvcorr \ &amp; \matwngradvcorr \end{cases} }\ &amp;\mathbf{w}[t+1] = \mathbf{w}[t] - \mu[t]\,\mathbf{a}[t]\,
matgradv \end{aligned} $$ . Matrix Inverse Square-root (Realizations) . Let \(\mathbf{m}[t]\) be a positive symmetric definite square matrix. There are several ways to realize its inverse square-root \( ar{\mathbf{d}}[t] = \mathbf{m}[t]^{	ext{-} rac{1}{2}}\). Typical cost is \(O(n^{3})\) per iteration. Full Eigenvalue Decomposition (EVD) . Compute the full eigenvalue decomposition \(\mathbf{m}[t] = \mathbf{U}\mathbf{\Lambda}\mathbf{U}^T\), then \( ar{\mathbf{d}}[t] = \mathbf{U}\mathbf{\Lambda}^{-1/2}\mathbf{U}^T\). Slower for large \(n\), with overhead of eigenvectors, but most accurate and numerically stable. $$  oxed{  egin{aligned} &amp;	ext{1: Eigenvalue decomposition}\ &amp;\quad \mathbf{U}\,\mathbf{\Lambda}\,\mathbf{U}^T = \mathbf{m}[t] \quad	ext{with}\quad \mathbf{\Lambda}=\operatorname{diag}(\lambda_1,\ldots,\lambda_n),\ \lambda_i&gt;0\ &amp;	ext{2: Form inverse square root of eigenvalues}\ &amp;\quad \mathbf{\Lambda}^{-1/2} = \operatorname{diag}(\lambda_1^{-1/2},\ldots,\lambda_n^{-1/2})\ &amp;	ext{3: Reconstruct inverse square root}\ &amp;\quad  ar{\mathbf{d}}[t] = \mathbf{U}\,\mathbf{\Lambda}^{-1/2}\,\mathbf{U}^T\ &amp; ar{\mathbf{d}}[t]\approx \mathbf{m}[t]^{-1/2} \end{aligned} } $$ To save time, an approximate result can be obtained via randomized eigenvalue decomposition, which involve using randomized methods to approximate the eigenvalue decomposition by computing only the top \(l\) eigencomponents where \(l \ll n\). Cost is now \(O(n^2l)\). Such low-rank approximations are cheaper than full EVD while maintaining reasonable accuracy for moderate \(n\). Newton-Schulz Iteration . For symmetric positive definite matrices, we may compute \( ar{\mathbf{d}}[t] = \mathbf{m}[t]^{-1/2}\), by maintaining two coupled polynomial sequences in matrix \(\mathbf{m}[t]\) that share the same residual (Higham, 2008). Initialize with a normalization constant \(c\), \(\mathbf{y}_0 = \mathbf{m}[t]/c\) and \(\mathbf{z}_0 = \mathbf{I}\). \[\mathbf{y}_{k+1} =  rac{1}{2}\mathbf{y}_k\,(3\mathbf{I} - \mathbf{z}_k\mathbf{y}_k)\] \[\mathbf{z}_{k+1} =  rac{1}{2}(3\mathbf{I} - \mathbf{z}_k\mathbf{y}_k)\,\mathbf{z}_k\] where as \(k	o\infty\), \(\mathbf{y}_k 	o \mathbf{m}[t]^{1/2}/\sqrt{c}\) (normalized) and \(\mathbf{z}_k 	o \sqrt{c}\,\mathbf{m}[t]^{-1/2}\) (normalized). Upon convergence, \( ar{\mathbf{d}}[t] \approx \mathbf{z}_k/\sqrt{c}\). Can monitor residual \(\mathbf{s}_k \;=\; \mathbf{I} - \mathbf{z}_k\,\mathbf{y}_k\), and stop when \(\| \mathbf{s}_k\| &lt; \epsilon\). It is well known that optimized BLAS libraries on GPUs can reduce wall‚Äëclock time to \(\approx O(n^{2}l)\), \(l \ll n\). Cheap for small number of iterations and moderate \(n\) because matrix‚Äìmatrix multiplications on GPUs achieve very high throughput and parallelism. $$  oxed{  egin{aligned} &amp;c = \|\mathbf{m}[t]\|\ &amp;\mathbf{y} = \mathbf{m}[t]/c\ &amp;\mathbf{z} = \mathbf{I}\ &amp;	extbf{for } k = 0, 1, 2, \ldots K\ &amp;\quad \mathbf{r} = 0.5\,(3\mathbf{I} - \mathbf{z}_k\,\mathbf{y}_k)\ &amp;\quad \mathbf{y} = \mathbf{y}\,\mathbf{r}\ &amp;\quad \mathbf{z} = \mathbf{r}\,\mathbf{z}\ &amp;	extbf{end for}\ &amp; ar{\mathbf{d}}[t] \approx \mathbf{z}/\sqrt{c} \, \end{aligned} } $$ . | Bottou, L., Curtis, F. E., &amp; Nocedal, J. (2018). Optimization Methods for Large-Scale Machine Learning. SIAM Review, 60(2), 223‚Äì311. | Moon, T. K., &amp; Stirling, W. C. (2000). Mathematical Methods and Algorithms for Signal Processing. Prentice Hall. | Van Trees, H. L., Bell, K. L., &amp; Tian, Z. (2013). Detection Estimation and Modulation Theory, Detection, Estimation, and Filtering Theory, Part I (2nd ed.). Wiley. | Diniz, P. S. R. (2020). Adaptive Filtering: Algorithms and Practical Implementation (5th edition). Springer International Publishing. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-29057-3 | Haykin, S. (2014). Adaptive Filter Theory (5th, intern.). Pearson. | Papoulis, A. (1977). Signal Analysis. McGraw-Hill College. | Higham, N. J. (2008). Functions of Matrices. Society for Industrial and Applied Mathematics. https://doi.org/10.1137/1.9780898717778 | Honig, M. L., &amp; Messerschmitt, D. G. (1984). Adaptive Filters: Structures, Algorithms and Applications. Kluwer Academic Publishers. | .
